The 94th (out of 150) track I wrote for my band back in 2008-2009, titled just "94".

Re-arranged and remade up to my current taste: added some middle-eastern heavy string instruments and some retro vibes, including the saw-souding, old-school distortion, hence the new, edgy title. Went out a bit creepy yet powerful. Dark progressive metal, maybe? idk, you tell me

videos.description:
Money. Dollars, Euro, the Yuan and so many others. 

They are the fuel that ignites the engines that our world runs on. Money is the lifeblood that flows through the veins of the worldâ€™s trade organism. 

This organismâ€™s most volatile organ, in the eyes of many, is China. 

Wars are fought over money and over who gets to be the most important part of the organism. Though in the modern era, these wars seldom require the use of arms and military force. 

Trade wars are an entirely different beast. While there is one possibly brewing between the U.S. and China, another lies on the horizon, and it involves the European Union. 

China and Europe seem to be adopting a top down approach to getting their economies back on track. Policy by directive and regulation. Is this our brave new world now? 

Why not let us just get on with it... and let market forces sort out the rest?

videos.title: Development of the West's counter-strategy towards Moscow | How We Got Here
videos.description:
Russia and Ukraine are both reeling. They have both recorded tactical operational and strategic successes and failures. As the third year nears its end are there any breakthroughs? 

Or are we in it for the long haul and are we prepared? 

The U.S., the U.K., and France have agreed to allow Ukraine to use the long-range missile systems they have provided, like the ATACMS, to strike deep into Russian territory. 

This is a massive shift in the Westâ€™s policy towards the war in Ukraine. Yet there are voices, that it is too little, too late. 

An escalation, some in Russia would say. A decision long overdue, others would say in the West. But can this war still be won in a way that the allies had wanted once Ukraine proved that it would not lose in mere days? 

Opinions remain divided, even among Western leadership where change has arrived. 

Historically, Russia has shown it can be beaten. Till this day, on its National Unity Day, it celebrates the fact that Poles no longer occupy Moscow as they did more than 400 years ago. Another time Russia was beaten was when its arguably geopolitically most powerful version, the Soviet Union, had broken its filed teeth on Finnish steel in 1940. 

Both Poland in the 1600s and Finland back then stood alone. Today, Europe tries to stand together to help Ukraine against Moscow and win the war. 

Join Jan Darasz and his guest: Witold Rodkiewicz, Senior Fellow, Russia Department, Centre for Eastern Studies for â€œHow We Got Hereâ€
